text: One popular interpretation of the song is of the singer feeling trapped by this woman (La Llorona) who has fallen in love with him. If he even thinks about leaving her, she weeps. He tries everything in his power to leave her, but he is trapped by pity for the woman. He wishes to be taken down to the river to be drowned, and so then his suffering can finally end. The suffering that the man goes through from being trapped in a relationship with a woman in a way parallels the suffering that the woman in the legend goes through from having her lover leave her. Other interpretation following the lyrics is that the "llorona" is the singers, a possible dessertor in the version here, deceased or married to another lover which would explain all the morbid references through the song and why he never seems to actually try to get to her "duelo" mourning, "campo santo" cementery, "ayer lloraba por verte llorona y ahora porque te v√≠" yesterday I cried for seeing you Llorona and now because I saw you. The Llorona is traditionally a Banshee like folk ghost that haunts her lover after having drowned her children and is now crying for her children and fortells dead to those who see it but is not really related to this song.  (taken from wiki)

text: Wonder how true it stays to the original tale, which varies. My mother told me the story when I was a teen (80s).   Her mother told her the story in the 60s.  We live by the border, near the Rio Grande (El Paso).  La Llorona was betrayed and abandoned by the father of her kids, she goes crazy with the pain, murders her children by drowning them in the Rio Grande river, and then kills herself.  Her spirit never rests and her sobs of pain and regret can be heard in the wind.

text: Hair as dark as night slips down her back, as she crouches low next to the creek and sinks her hands into the cool water. A dress as white as her hair is black drapes over her frame. It‚Äôs a haunting image, made even more eery by the fact that there is no sound save the tinkling water of the stream . . . But then, the rough hiccup of a woman crying splits through the silence, growing louder and louder until the woman with the long black hair and the white-as-white dress turns and looks directly at you.  Still, the desperate wailing surrounds you, picking up speed, picking up strength, until there is the very present fear that something is wrong.  And her face?  It‚Äôs not human. Maybe blank with no features at all, no eyes, no nose, no mouth from whence the wailing came.  . . . Or worse, her face is not blank. There are eyes, a nose, a mouth, but they are elongated‚Äîprotruding‚Äîin the shape of a donkey‚Äôs or a horse‚Äôs.  Hers is the face of La Llorona, or The Weeping Woman‚Äîand the fact that you‚Äôve met her acquaintance? We wish you the best of luck, for, as the legend goes, her presence almost always meets with death, disease or something else horrifyingly bad
author: Patrick O'Neill

text: I remember my parents telling me about la llorona.   I always listened for her cries when we were out, she genuinely terrified me.   Like, I knew about el coco and witches and shit, but my uncle pointed out UFOs and called them witches and I had no idea why I was supposed to be scared. Probably because Harry Potter was the first thing that came to mind when I thought about witchcraft.   I would walk to the darkest rooms in my house and look deep into closets with no end and even keep my eyes open when I was supposed to be asleep and I had no idea why the cucuy was supposed to be scary, so I didn't give a shit. But la llorona?   Holy shit, I tried not to think of her because I was told she only cried for those who listened, and sometimes I was a little brave (only in the car) and looked out the window to see if I'd see her passing figure or hear her sobs echo.   Just, holy shit. Imagine bloody mary with the longest fingernails ever crying like the witch from Left4Dead, but instead of simple sobs she was chanting "mis hijos" (my children). I imagined that as her, and if she felt even the tiniest bit of my glance (like a fucking enderman in minecraft) she'd start chasing me and threatening to drown me too. I was scared to death.  You know how I mentioned the dark and el coco? There were two big windows in my childhood bedroom. One behind my bed with the curtains always shut and another to the right with a great view of the outside world if one was low enough to the ground or lying down (I was both, since I was a child). If you were tall enough, you could look _into_  my room through the blinds, but no one was tall enough since the window was pretty high and the bottom half was covered by an AC.   Anyway, instead thinking about witches peering inside to try to recruit me or sacrifice me or el coco hiding under my bed (or in my closet, which scared me more than the bottom of my bed), I always focused my hearing on the outside because I was trying to catch her wails. I feared her cries would come closer and closer until I saw her tall dark figure through the window and then her eyes peering down at me, still crying and her sobbing for her children. Just.  La Llorona scares me, man. El coco and witches were scary, and I mostly received threats about el coco coming for me if I didn't do basic stuff like sleep or do my chores. Witches were looming figures I occasionally heard about. Bad role models, evil wenches that I should avoid, nothing actually scary since I only "saw" them once, but I guess they felt more real than the cucuy.   But la Llorona was the reason I never left my parents side when we weren't at home, especially considering how many times we went to places surrounded by dark woods or empty streets. She wasn't the slenderman or the slit-mouthed woman, she was both. She could follow me everywhere and wait outside my home for me.   I have never considered that she could have very well entered my house. Wtf.

text: To y'all wondering, "la llorona" is based on a true story, This Mexican woman loved a Spanish man and they had 3 kids. They kept their relationship on the low. He then left her for a wealthy woman, and she was pissed, out of anger and revenge seeking, She then drowned her kids. She realized what she had done and turned herself crazy looking for the bodies of her drowned kids.    Then the myths kick in when people start saying they seen her, and or heard her before, which I call bullshit. Until it happens to me, I won't believe the myths.   Many people have altered the story to scare their kids straight. For example, one version says she kidnaps kid's that are alone. (parents altered this story so their kids don't wander off.) You get the point, that is why so many versions of the story exist.

text: I feel like they got the story wrong. So basically a young beautiful lady(poor) lived in Mexico. She was the most beautiful girl there. A rich young man fell in love with her, and they eventually had kids. (Take note that the rich father did not like her, so they had to run away with each other) they had two kids, both boys. The father always went out, leaving the young mother and the kids alone. The father used to always bring presents to everybody. But soon, the father became distant to the mother, only bringing presents to the kids. He then started to come back rarely. And then finally, he just never came back. A few years later(after she became old, and less beautiful) she was strolling along a river with her two kids. When all of a sudden, a familiar young man came in a carriage, and he had a beautiful young woman who looked very wealthy(somebody that the young man‚Äôs father would be proud of) he greeted the kids and glanced at the mother. And gave a smug look at her. Then they went away. Enraged, embarrassed, and humiliated, she pulled her kids to the river and threw them into the water. After realizing what she has done, she threw her self into too, hoping to reunite with he two lost kids in the afterlife. See, she couldn‚Äôt. Because she has done the two worst sins(murder and suicide) Now, she is forced to walk along the river, crying hoping to find her children. If you hear her crying, use that as a warning because if she sees and/or touches you, you will have bad luck for the rest of your life. For children it‚Äôs fatal, because she will come to a kid. Thinking it‚Äôs her lost children. When she realizes it‚Äôs not hers, she will throw the kid into the water. So basically, she‚Äôs not looking for your children. She‚Äôs looking for her children. (I‚Äôm sorry I‚Äôm just so triggered about this)

text: In Mexican folklore, La Llorona (pronounced [la  ùo.Àà…æo.na], "The Weeping Woman") is the ghost of a woman who drowned her children and now cries while looking for them in the river, often causing misfortune to those who are near or hear her. There is no credible source or evidence to the events that inspired the tale/legend of La Llorona.      Maria, angry and hurt, took her children to a river and drowned them in a blind rage. She realized what she had done and searched for them, but the river had already carried them away. Days later, she was found dead on the river bank. Challenged at the gates of heaven for the whereabouts of her children, she was not permitted to enter the afterlife until she finds them. Stuck between the land of the living and the dead, she spends eternity looking for her lost children. She is always heard weeping for her children, earning her the name "La Llorona."[1] It is said that if you hear her crying, you are to run the opposite way. If you hear her cries, they could bring misfortune or even death. Many parents in Latin America use this story to scare their children from staying out too late.

text: "The Curse Of La Llorona" released in Australia as "The Curse Of The Weeping Woman" is a thriller horror film based on the Mexican folklore of La Llorona. She is the ghost of a woman who drowned her children and now cries while looking for them in the river, often causing misfortune to those who are near or hear her. There is no credible source or evidence to the events that inspired the tale of La Llorona. This film is the sixth of The Conjuring Universe directed by Michael Chavez which is much much better then the previous release, "The Nun". There are moments of significant fright and suspense which ensures its entertainment value. However rushed conclusion felt as bad as rushing through a large plate of nachos with extra jalapenos. By the way am I glad I speak castellano (Spanish) as there were parts spoken in Spanish that lacked interpretation...  I rate it 2.5 out of 5.

His mom walked in his room cause she heard it too and she told him to ignore it. That was pretty much all he told me...My real dads story however was different. My dad was with his friend walking around the streets of Colombia when he heard the crying and as soon as he heard it he ran. He said his friend saw her and he described her to have white dress (obviously), she was floating in the air, and she was just floating towards him and as he ran away she started to float after him. text: LA LLORONA  La Llorona is a legend of Mexican folklore üá≤üáΩ born of Aztec and Spanish miscegenation. Many saw, it is a beautiful woman, tall, thin and dressed in white; He was seen near the rivers and lakes, as if floating, he is suffering for the souls of his children, and a lament of pain announces his pain ... Oh my children! But what happened? Why would a mother kill her children? In Mexico City, There is a sixteenth-century version that persists among the elderly who say they have seen it on the streets, in cemeteries, in churches, in houses, on train tracks, or in any lonely place where perhaps she could find her children. People remember that one night they began to hear screams and groans of pain; no one wanted to leave, everyone thought it was a woman that could have been abandoned, the sobs were clear from someone who was suffering, but they showed up every night. Some people had the courage to see who it was, what was their surprise to see a beautiful woman dressed in white and her huge hair walking through different neighborhoods. Some people curious to know what their grief had taken hold followed her, but upon arriving in the river, she disappeared among the waters. There were so many regrets every night that people began to call him "the woman crying," a mongrel woman who they say was the soul of a young woman lost in love with a Spaniard who came from the old continent, he was the father of their three children. As it was not well seen that he fell in love with a stranger, his family turned their backs on her, leaving her alone with the decision to make a living with her lover, however he was not interested in formalizing their lives in marriage. Those who tell the legend say that every time she approached him to see the possibility of formalizing the relationship so that the children had a surname, he refused or avoided the conversation. One day the beautiful woman learned that he was married to a lady of birth in Spain and would leave her with everything and children. With uncontrollable anger and without thinking of things, she took her children and drowned them in the river and once completely alone, she could no longer with her position of conscience and took her life. Time passed and this story began to come to life with the screams of the woman who were heard every night around 11 at night. So the population defined by making a curfew where people had to shelter themselves at home. They could not even look out the windows because the face of a skeleton was aching from house to house screaming with a howl Oh my children! It was the woman who cried asked if anyone saw them. The soul of the weeping woman continues to search for her creatures in Mexico City, lamenting the remaining streets on earth for her actions, she will clearly not see them again, since they, being innocent souls, are angels in heaven.  And did you hear your cries?
author: ANDRES MORA

The use of music was quite refrained compared to shitty blockbuster horror movies that have generic orchestral music playing CONSTANTLY in the background, and hardly ever use silence. Anyway, it's better than shit like Annabel, the Nun, the Conjuring, any one of the "girl-gets-possessed-and-priest-has-to-exorcise-the-demon" movies with the girls name in the title.
